Spatial distribution and local integration of migrants in Ireland

Daniel Capistrano, Evan Carron-Kee, Lúcás Rohan et al.

October 2025

Intro

Objectives

  • Geographical distribution of migrants in Ireland

  • Characteristics of the communities where migrants live

  • Residential segregation across neighbourhoods

  • Factors associated with distribution and residential segregation

Context

Literature - Spatial distribution and integration

  • Integration as a spatialised process (Gilmartin and Dagg 2021);

  • Different paths to integration depending on origin (Heath and Schneider 2021);

  • Housing as marker and mean of integration (Ager and Strang 2008) and space for bridges, links and bonds;

Literature - Correlates

  • High concentration in areas with high share of privately rented accommodation (Fahey et al. 2019)

  • Housing tenure, affordability and availability (mcginnity_monitoring_2024?; Lima 2025)

Previous report

  • Small decrease in foreign-born segregation between 2011 and 2016.

  • “We might expect greater residential clustering among more tightly defined groups that share linguistic or cultural characteristics.”

Structure

  • Chapter 1: Literature review
  • Chapter 2: Geographical distribution and segregation
  • Chapter 3: Characteristics of local communities
  • Chapter 4: Local policy context and implications
  • Chapter 5: Conclusions

Methods

Data sources

  • CSO SAPS 2016 and 2022;
  • Small Area frequencies by country of birth
  • IPAS centres occupancy 2021-2025
  • Auxiliary data (e.g. HSE Service Dir., School register, Garda stations)
  • Semi-structured interviews and focus group

Data analysis

  1. LEA-level visualisations
  2. Descriptive analyses of size and change by CoB
  3. Indices: Dissimilarity, Isolation, and Diversity
  4. Regression analyses of 2 and 3
  5. Thematic analysis of qualitative data

Index of Dissimilarity

Move the sliders to set the number of foreign-born residents in each small area. Click the button to calculate the index.

import {Inputs} from "@observablehq/inputs"
import {Plot} from "@observablehq/plot"
viewof ui = {
  const container = html`<div style="font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 900px; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: flex-start;">
    <!-- Left Column for Sliders -->
    <div id="sliders-column" style="flex: 1; margin-right: 20px;">

      <div id="sliders" style="margin-bottom: 1em;"></div>

      <!-- Styled Button -->
      <button id="calculate-btn" style="
        margin-top: 1em;
        padding: 1em 2em;
        font-size: 16px;
        background-color: steelblue;
        color: white;
        border: none;
        border-radius: 4px;
        cursor: pointer;
      ">
        Calculate Dissimilarity Index
      </button>

      <div id="result" style="margin-top: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Right Column for Plot -->
    <div id="plot-column" style="flex: 1; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: stretch;">
      <div id="chart" style="width: 100%; max-width: 400px;"></div>
    </div>
  </div>`

  // Constants
  const AREAS = ["Small Area A", "Small Area B", "Small Area C", "Small Area D"]
  const N_RESIDENTS = 100

  // Create sliders and store their elements
  const sliders = AREAS.map(area => {
    const label = html`<label style="display: block; margin-top: 1em; font-size: 14px">${area}</label>`
    const input = Inputs.range([0, N_RESIDENTS], {value: 20, step: 5})
    container.querySelector("#sliders").appendChild(label)
    container.querySelector("#sliders").appendChild(input)
    return input
  })

  // Button click event
  container.querySelector("#calculate-btn").onclick = () => {
    const g1_counts = []
    const g2_counts = []
    let g1_total = 0
    let g2_total = 0

    for (const slider of sliders) {
      const g1 = slider.value
      const g2 = N_RESIDENTS - g1
      g1_counts.push(g1)
      g2_counts.push(g2)
      g1_total += g1
      g2_total += g2
    }

    const D = 0.5 * g1_counts.reduce((sum, g1, i) => {
      const g2 = g2_counts[i]
      return sum + Math.abs(g1 / g1_total - g2 / g2_total)
    }, 0)

    const percentD = +(D * 100).toFixed(1)
    container.querySelector("#result").textContent = `Dissimilarity Index: ${percentD}`

    // Get the actual height of the sliders column
    const slidersHeight = container.querySelector("#sliders-column").offsetHeight

    // Create the plot using that height
    const plot = Plot.plot({
      y: {label: "", domain: [0, 100]},
      x: {label: null},
      marks: [
        Plot.barY([{index: "Dissimilarity", value: percentD}], {
          x: "index",
          y: "value",
          fill: "steelblue"
        }),
        Plot.text([{index: "Dissimilarity", value: percentD}], {
          x: "index",
          y: "value",
          text: d => `${d.value}`,
          dy: -6,
          fontWeight: "bold",
          fill: "black"
        })
      ],
      style: {fontSize: "14px"},
      height: slidersHeight
    })

    const chartDiv = container.querySelector("#chart")
    chartDiv.innerHTML = ""
    chartDiv.appendChild(plot)
  }

  return container
}

Correlates of segregation

Qualitative research

  • Insights on local governance of integration (e.g. LAITs, local authorities)

  • Three interviews and one focus group completed

Qual - initial insights

  • Missed opportunities: local insight not being used on sensitive issues, e.g. IP accommodation.

  • Local flexibility: Appreciation of integration as a new competency in local government; Ability to solve local issues through communication 

  • Dependence on central gov.: Improved relationship, some local work focuses on providing info. or seeking fund from central gov., rather than acting with autonomy. Still lack of autonomy or authority on accommodation, despite its centrality on integration;

  • Structural barriers: Issues with mental health; Lack of transport

Summary

  • Higher concentration of foreign-born in cities
  • Higher concentration in areas with high share of active pop. (Devlin, McGuinness, and Whelan 2025; mcginnity_monitoring_2024?)
  • Low levels of segregation overall, but high for specific groups
  • Significant reduction in segregation for specific groups
  • Further analysis

Limitations

  • Residential only small part of segregation (Buhr 2024)

  • Aggregate measures

  • Lack of migrant perspectives (ethical and time constraints)

Literature - Correlates (host attitudes)

  • Contact (Pettigrew and Tropp 2006) and extended contact (Zhou et al. 2019) reduce prejudice;
  • Local migrant-share association with attitudes in rural Ireland (Laurence, McGinnity, and Murphy 2025);
  • Segregation mediates the relationship between migrant-share and attitudes in the UK (Borkowska and Laurence 2025)

Literature - Correlates (health)

  • Association with perception of social exclusion (Liu, Huang, and Zhang 2018)

  • Bridging social capital as moderator of anti-immigrant climate and unmet healthcare needs (Neureiter and Waldmann 2025)
